Numerical Differentiation Methods Comparison in Excel
Overview
This project demonstrates the implementation of several numerical differentiation methods using **Microsoft Excel**. The objective is to approximate the first derivative of a mathematical function and compare the accuracy of each finite difference method through error analysis.

The function analyzed is:
\[f(x)=x^2\ln(x)+x\]
Different finite difference formulas are implemented and compared with the analytical derivative to determine which method provides the most accurate approximation.

Objectives
- Implement numerical differentiation using Microsoft Excel.
- Compare the accuracy of several finite difference methods.
- Calculate approximation errors for each method.
- Visualize the function and error comparison using charts.

Methods
The following numerical differentiation methods are implemented:
- Forward Difference O(h)
- Backward Difference O(h)
- Central Difference O(h²)
- Forward Difference O(h²)
- Central Difference O(h⁴)

Results
| Method | Approximation Error |
|---------|--------------------:|
| Forward Difference O(h) | 4.284% |
| Backward Difference O(h) | 4.209% |
| Central Difference O(h²) | 0.038% |
| Forward Difference O(h²) | 0.072% |
| Central Difference O(h⁴) | **0.000047%** |
The comparison shows that the **Fourth-Order Central Difference** achieves the smallest approximation error, making it the most accurate method among those tested.

